com.mmontuori.binarytree

Class BinaryTree<A,B>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.mmontuori.binarytree.BinaryTree<A,B>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - the key object type
    B - the value object type
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    IntStringBinaryTree

    public abstract class BinaryTree<A,B>
extends java.lang.Object
    BinaryTree is the class implementing the binary search tree algorithms. The class is capable of providing different tree traversal such as: in order, pre order, post order, and reverse in order. It is also capable of providing the total size, right and left sizes to examine if the tree is unbalanced
    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Michael Montuori

      • compare

        public abstract int compare(Node<A,B> a,
          Node<A,B> b)
        abstract method that must be implemented to compare 2 nodes. The method must return '-1' if node a is < than node b, '0' if node a is = to node b, and '1' if node a is > then node b. The return code allows the BinaryTree class to store the node in the appropriate side of the binary tree (left or right)
        Parameters:
        a - the first node reference to compare
        b - the second node reference to compare
        Returns:
        '-1' if ab

      • addNode

        public void addNode(Node<A,B> node)
        adds a Node reference to the binary search tree. The first node added becomes the root node, the subsequent elements are added based on comparing the node to add to the existing nodes in the tree.
        Parameters:
        node - the node to add to the binary search tree

      • traverseReverseOrder

        public void traverseReverseOrder(Node<A,B> currentNode)
        This method is used to traverse the binary tree in descending order, meaning biggest node first, smallest at last. This is achieved by traversing the right subtree first, visiting the root, and traversing the left subtree. Every time a node is iterated, the orderedNode function is called with the current node as a parameter
        Parameters:
        currentNode - the actual focused node

      • traverseInOrder

        public void traverseInOrder(Node<A,B> currentNode)
        This method is used to traverse the binary tree in ascending order, meaning smallest node first, biggest at last. This is achieved by traversing the left subtree first, visiting the root, and traversing the right subtree. Every time a node is iterated, the orderedNode function is called with the current node as a parameter
        Parameters:
        currentNode - the actual focused node

      • traversePreOrder

        public void traversePreOrder(Node<A,B> currentNode)
        This method is used to traverse the binary tree in ascending order, meaning smallest node first, biggest at last, with the exception that the root node is visited first. This is achieved by visiting the root, traversing the left subtree, and traversing the right subtree.
        Parameters:
        currentNode - the actual focused node

      • traversePostOrder

        public void traversePostOrder(Node<A,B> currentNode)
        This method is used to traverse the binary tree in ascending order, meaning smallest node first, biggest at last, with the exception that the root node is visited last. This is achieved by traversing the left subtree first, traversing the right subtree, and visiting the root.
        Parameters:
        currentNode - the actual focused node

      • findNode

        Returns:
